                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, July 24 (PTI): The Centre today approved setting up of Indias first ever military tribunal.           
	There will be a principal bench in the capital and eight regional branches to hear grievances of the armed forces personnel.           
	The tribunal would be headed by a retired Supreme Court judge or a retired high court chief justice. Besides the chairperson, the tribunal would have 14 judicial members and 15 administrative members.          
	A staggering 9,800 cases of the armed forces personnel pending in civil courts would now stand transferred to the newly set up tribunal, according to information and broadcasting minister Priya Ranjan Dasmunsi.                  
	Dubai (PTI): The UAE will allow visitors of all nationalities to enter the country on a tourist visa for 30 days under new rules that come into effect from July 29. The new rules will encourage the tourism sector in the country, an official of Dubai naturalisation and residency department said. Under the existing rules, Indians and West Asians are not eligible for tourist visas.                  
	Thiruvananthapuram (PTI): A block of mortar fell from the ceiling on Kerala chief minister V.S. Achuthanandans bed on Thursday morning, but he was unhurt. The 85-year-old politician had gone for his routine early bath.                  
	Lucknow: Six Shiv Sena activists of Agra on Thursday tried to offer prayers inside the Taj Mahal compound, claiming there had originally been a Shiv temple at the site. We saw them bring out flowers and incense sticks from their bags. We had been alerted by intelligence officials that Shiv Sainiks might disrupt communal harmony at the monument, an official said. They were taken into custody and later released.                  
	 Chandigarh (PTI): Six people were killed and 12 injured in a collision between a private bus and a harvest combine in on Thursday. Chief minister Parkash Singh Badal announced a grant of Rs 1 lakh to the family of each of the dead and Rs 50,000 and Rs 25,000 to victims with serious and minor injuries respectively.                                                                                                                         
